The paper deals with statistical properties of non-linear transformations of random variables, which is a topic closely related to information theory and estimation. The paper specifically mentions the use of these properties in communication, estimation, and information theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses linear regression analysis, which is a common tool in machine learning and statistics, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions Gaussian mixtures, which are commonly used in statistical modeling, making cs.SI (Statistics) a possible sub-category. The paper also discusses the computation of signal-to-noise ratio and mean-squared error, which are topics related to numerical analysis, making cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of these properties in additive non-Gaussian channels, which is a topic related to control systems, making cs.SY (Systems and Control) a possible sub-category.
